<h2><a name="ldexp" id="ldexp">ldexp</a></h2>
<div class="level2">

<p>

Syntax:

</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="co2">#include &lt;cmath&gt;</span>
    <span class="kw4">double</span> ldexp<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">double</span> num<span class="sy0">,</span> <span class="kw4">int</span> exp <span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy0">;</span></pre>
<p>

The ldexp() function returns num * (2 ^ exp). And get this: if an overflow
occurs, HUGE_VAL is returned.
</p>

<p>
C++ also provides the following overloaded forms:

</p>
<pre class="c code c++" style="font-family:monospace;">    <span class="co2">#include &lt;cmath&gt;</span>
    <span class="kw4">float</span> ldexp<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">float</span> num<span class="sy0">,</span> <span class="kw4">int</span> exp <span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy0">;</span> <span class="co1">// same as ldexpf() in C99</span>
    <span class="kw4">long</span> <span class="kw4">double</span> ldexp<span class="br0">&#40;</span> <span class="kw4">long</span> <span class="kw4">double</span> num<span class="sy0">,</span> <span class="kw4">int</span> exp <span class="br0">&#41;</span><span class="sy0">;</span> <span class="co1">// same as ldexpl() in C99</span></pre>
<p>
Related Topics: <a href="frexp" class="wikilink1" title="c:math:frexp">frexp</a>, <a href="modf" class="wikilink1" title="c:math:modf">modf</a>

</p>

